{{Expand Norwegian|Johannes Aarflot|date=July 2013}} {{Expand Norwegian (Nynorsk)|Johannes Aarflot|date=July 2013}} '''Johannes Amundsson Aarflot''' (29 October 1824 – 3 November 1891) was a [[Norway|Norwegian]] businessman and member of the [[Norwegian Parliament]].
Aarflot was born on the farm Årflot at [[Ørsta]] (''Aarflot i Ørsta'') in [[Møre og Romsdal]], Norway. He was the son of Amund Knutsson Aarflot (1788–1860) and his wife, [[Berte Canutte Aarflot]] (1795–1859) who was a Christian hymnwriter in the [[Haugean]] tradition (''haugianere''). From 1841 he was an employee at a bookstore in [[Ålesund]]. In 1860, he opened his own bookstore, ''Aarflots Bokhandel'' (now Ark Aarflot).<ref>{{cite web |url= https://snl.no/haugianere|title= haugianere|publisher= Store norske leksikon |author= Hallgeir Elstad|accessdate= June 15, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.dokpro.uio.no/cgi-bin/stad/matr50|title= Aarflot in Ørsta herad i Møre og Romsdal|publisher= Matrikkelutkastet av 1950 |accessdate= June 10, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url= https://lokalhistoriewiki.no/index.php/Aarflot|title= Aarflot|publisher = lokalhistoriewiki.no |accessdate= June 10, 2016}}</ref>
He was a member of the city council in Alesund during 1861. He served as the mayor of the town in 1864, 1876–81 and 1883-91. He also served as one of the Settlement Commissioners (''Forlikskommissær'') on the District Conciliation Board (''Forliksråd '') from 1870. Aarflot became a member of the Norwegian Parliament from the [[Conservative Party (Norway)|Conservative Party]], representing [[Aalesund]] og [[Molde]] during four terms (1868-1869, 1871-1873, 1880–82, 1889-1891).<ref>[https://lokalhistoriewiki.no/index.php/Leksikon:Forlikskommisjon ''Forlikskommisjon'' (lokalhistoriewiki.no)]</ref><ref name=nsd>{{cite web|url=http://www.nsd.uib.no/polsys/index.cfm?urlname=&lan=&MenuItem=N1_1&ChildItem=&State=collapse&UttakNr=33&person=10021|title=Johannes Aarflot|publisher=Norwegian Social Science Data Services (NSD)|language=Norwegian|accessdate=17 December 2010}}</ref><ref name=nbl>{{cite encyclopedia|title=Berte Canutte Aarflot|encyclopedia=[[Norsk biografisk leksikon]]|first=Jostein|last=Fet|editor=[[Knut Helle|Helle, Knut]]|publisher=Kunnskapsforlaget|location=Oslo|url=http://www.snl.no/.nbl_biografi/Berte_Canutte_Aarflot/utdypning|language=Norwegian|accessdate=17 December 2010}}</ref> ==References== {{Reflist|1}} ==Other sources== *{{Cite journal | last = Grytten | first = Ola H. | authorlink = Ola Honningdal Grytten | editor-last = Andresen | editor-first = Nils A. | editor-link = Nils August Andresen | title = Protestantisk etikk og entreprenørskapets ånd | journal = [[Minerva (Norwegian periodical)|Minerva]] | year = 2010 | volume = 86 | issue = 4 | page = 72 |trans-title= The Protestant Ethic and the Spirit of Entrepreneurship | publisher = [[Conservative Students' Association (Norway)|Conservative Students' Association]] | location = Oslo | language = Norwegian | issn = 0805-7842 | oclc = 477895639}} {{Use dmy dates|date=January 2012}}
