[[File:Paul Chaffey.JPG|thumb|Paul Chaffey.]]
'''Paul André Chaffey''' (born 10 July 1965) is a Norwegian businessperson and politician, who represented the [[Socialist Left Party (Norway)|Socialist Left Party]] until 1997. He is now [[State Secretary]] to [[Minister of Local Government and Modernisation (Norway)|Minister of Local Government]] [[Jan Tore Sanner]], and a supporter of the [[Conservative Party of Norway|Conservative Party]] since 2000.

He was born in [[Oslo]] as a son of university lecturer Patrick Nigel Chaffey (1938–2006) and advisor Arnhild Mæhle (born 1945). He grew up in [[Bærum]], and finished secondary school at [[Valler Upper Secondary School]] in 1984. At the [[University of Oslo]] he minored in [[political science]] in 1985–1986 before minoring in history in 1988–1989. He became involved in the [[Socialist Youth (Norway)|Socialist Youth]] at a young age, and worked as their county secretary in [[Oslo]] from 1984 to 1985. From 1986 to 1988 he was the organizational secretary of the nationwide organization. He was a board member in Bærum from 1983 to 1984, in Akershus from 1984 to 1985 and then nationwide from 1985 to 1990. From 1988 to 1990 he led the organization. From 1986 to 1989 he was a member of the national board and central committee of the [[Socialist Left Party (Norway)|Socialist Left Party]]. He released two books in this period: ''Lik rett til utdanning'' in 1986 and ''Grønn framtid?: vår miljøpolitiske utfordring'' in 1989.<ref name=bio>{{stortingetbio|PC}}</ref>

He was elected as a member of the [[Parliament of Norway]] in [[Norwegian parliamentary election, 1989|1989]] and [[Norwegian parliamentary election, 1993|1993]], representing the constituency Akershus. In the first term he was a member of the [[Standing Committee on Foreign Affairs|Standing Committee on Foreign and Constitutional Affairs]] and the [[Enlarged Committee on Foreign Affairs and Defence|Enlarged Committee on Foreign and Constitutional Affairs]]. In the second term he was the secretary of the [[Standing Committee on Energy and the Environment]].<ref name=bio/>

In 1997 he left politics, and was hired as an advisor in [[Statoil]]. After a short time as director of occupational safety and health, strategy and communications in 1999, he was the director of marketing from 1999 to 2001. In 2001 he was hired as managing director of [[Abelia (organization)|Abelia]],<ref name=bio/> an [[employers' organisation]] organized under the national [[Confederation of Norwegian Enterprise]].<ref>{{cite encyclopedia|year=2007|title=Abelia|encyclopedia=[[Store norske leksikon]]|editor=Henriksen, Petter|publisher=Kunnskapsforlaget|location=Oslo|url=http://www.snl.no/Abelia|language=Norwegian|accessdate=25 January 2010}}</ref> He has also been chair of the [[Norwegian Institute of International Affairs]] from 2002 to 2005, a board member of ''Europaprogrammet'' from 1990 to 1997<ref name=bio/> and of the University of Oslo.<ref>{{cite news|title=Vil kaste Chaffey|last=Haarde|first=Margrethe Zacho|date=30 November 2007|work=Dagens Næringsliv|page=50|language=Norwegian}}</ref>

In line with his change of career, Chaffey has been known for denouncing his former connections to the socialist movement. He has stated that he voted [[Norwegian Labour Party|Labour]] in [[Norwegian parliamentary election, 1997|1997]], the very same year that he concluded his parliamentary representation for the Socialist Left Party, and in the 2000s he began voting [[Conservative Party (Norway)|Conservative]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Svinger pisken over SV|last=Skard|first=Kristian|date=16 November 2006|work=Dagens Næringsliv|page=18|language=Norwegian}}</ref> In 2008 he explained his move to the right to have been as he realized "that the [[market economy]] works", and even spoke at the national conference of the [[Progress Party (Norway)|Progress Party]] where he praised its members.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dagbladet.no/tekstarkiv/artikkel.php?id=5001080054368&tag=item&words=per%3Bsandberg%3Bsv%3Bper+sandberg|title=SV-avhopper gir ros til Frp|last=Slaaen|first=Cathrine|date=4 May 2008|work=Dagbladet|language=Norwegian}}</ref>

